ominent_name_reason":"Capt. William Coit — Yale 1761; \"The Great Red Dragon\" (wore scarlet cloak); commanded schooner Harrison, one of first vessels of the Continental Navy; present at Battle of Bunker Hill; claimed first American to turn British flag upside down; commander of \"Oliver Cromwell\" (1776); captured by Benedict Arnold 1781; DAR Patriot A023936.","burial":{"cemetery_id":"CEM865"},"tags":["revolutionary_war"],"sources":[{"short":"Edward Hooker 1909","page":"Entry 248"},{"short":"CAPTAIN WILLIAM COIT by P.H. Woodward, Connecticut Historical Society, 1879"}],"cross_connections":[],"gender":"male","number_of_marriages":1,"notable":{"is_notable":true,"notable_category":[],"notable_blurb":"“The Great Red Dragon” of the Revolution","primary_url":"https://boston1775.blogspot.com/2010/02/capt-william-coit-describes-his-ship.html","primary_url_label":"Boston 1775"},"education":[{"school_name":"Yale College","dates":"1761","type":"undergraduate"}],"military_service":[{"war":"American Revolutionary War","branch":"Continental Army then naval service","rank":"Captain","unit":"4th Company, 6th Connecticut Regiment; schooner Harrison; ship Oliver Cromwell","notes":"Covered the retreat at Bunker Hill; commanded the Harrison from Oct 1775 under Washington’s written instructions; later the privateer America; captured when Arnold burned New London, Sept 6, 1781"}],"bio":{"title":"Captain","display_name":"Captain William Coit","nickname":"The Great Red Dragon","notes":"Known for wearing a scarlet cloak","first_name":"William","last_name":"Coit","married_names":[]},"residence":{},"baptism":{},"research_tags":[],"research_sources":[],"documents":[],"naming_inspiration":[],"institutions":[{"institution_id":"INST022","relationship":"alumnus","years":"1761"}],"landmarks":[],"artworks":[],"quotes":[],"narrative_blocks":[{"number":1,"category":"military","header":"Captain of one of America's first warships","body":"In late 1775 he commanded the schooner Harrison — one of the first vessels commissioned by Congress under General Washington. He intercepted two British supply ships and brought them into Plymouth harbor."},{"number":2,"category":"military","header":"Made British prisoners stand on Plymouth Rock","body":"He landed the captured British prisoners on Plymouth Rock, where they 'gave three cheers, and wished success to American arms,' per the Pennsylvania Journal of 1775. The act inverted Plymouth's founding myth: now British prisoners stood on the rock."},{"number":3,"category":"character","header":"The Great Red Dragon — scarlet cloak","body":"He was tall, portly, soldierly in bearing, frank, jovial, somewhat eccentric, and very liberal. He wore a scarlet cloak that earned him the nickname 'The Great Red Dragon.'"},{"number":4,"category":"military","header":"First American to invert the British flag","body":"He claimed to be 'the first man in the States who turned his majesty's bunting upside down' when he captured British vessels in late 1775. The symbolic act came early in the naval war."},{"number":5,"category":"military","header":"“Cohorns that Noah had in the Ark”","body":"His November 1775 letter savaged his own schooner: cannon “brought by the Lords Say and Seal” in 1635, swivels “never fired since” 1620, a deck that broke through over the magazine, smoke that “serves for bedding, victuals, drink and choking.” Firing both guns of a side, he wrote, would split her “from gunwale to her keelson.”"}],"slug":"william-coit-1742"},"X00114":{"id":"X00114","classification":{"include_in_path_calculation":false,"descent_from_thomas_hooker":false,"descent_from_john_talcott":false,"is_thomas_descendant":false,"is_talcott_descendant":false,"is_easter_egg":false},"birth":{"year":1741,"month":1,"day":27,"city":"New London","state":"Connecticut"},"death":{"year":1813,"month":5,"day":18,"city":"New York","state":"New York"},"parents":{"mother_research_notes":"Sarah Christophers","father_research_notes":"Capt. John Prentiss of New London — com